'''Chelsea Common''' was the ground of [[Chelsea Cricket Club]] in the 18th century, an area that virtually disappeared under building work in the 19th century.<ref>[https://www.rbkc.gov.uk/leisure-and-culture/parks/chelsea-common Chelsea Common]</ref> Records have survived of five [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important matches]] between 1731 and 1789 which either involved the Chelsea club or were played on the common. The first, played on the common for the high stake of 50 [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]], was Chelsea v [[Fulham Cricket Club|Fulham]] on Tuesday, 13 July 1731. Fulham won.<ref name=DC9>Waghorn, ''Dawn of Cricket'', p. 9.</ref> There was a return at [[Parsons Green]] on Tuesday, 10 August 1731, which Fulham won by 3 [[run (cricket)|runs]].<ref name=DC9/> On Tuesday, 26 June 1733, Fulham again hosted Chelsea at Parsons Green, this time for 30 guineas, but the result of this match is unknown.<ref>Buckley, ''FL18C'', p. 8.</ref> On Monday, 16 August 1736, there was an inter-county match on the common between [[Middlesex county cricket teams|Middlesex]] and [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]]. The stake was 50 guineas and Middlesex won by 9 runs.<ref>Buckley, ''FL18C'', p. 13.</ref> The last match found in the records was on Thursday, 10 and Friday, 11 September 1789 when Chelsea played [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) in Marlborough Gardens, Chelsea. This match, which was of dubious status, was probably drawn after a postponement.<ref>Buckley, ''FLPVC'', p. 22.</ref>

